Can you prove that orangutans use the wildlife corridor?

Lukmann Haqeem

01 November, 2021



Probably the best approach to monitor orangutan movement is to fit a GPS tracking device on the animal. However, finding a single animal can be very challenging. Moreover, this method often involves shooting the animal from tree with the tranquilizer, the animal could fall to the ground and get injured or even die. Even if safe capture is possible and surveyors can fit tracker on the animal, there is also concern that the animal will grab and remove the tracker out because it is just too nimble and too strong (Trayford and Farmer 2012). Perhaps a safer approach to monitor movement is to follow the animal wherever it goes and records its position regularly with a GPS device (Schaik, Damerius, and Isler 2013). While it is easy for orangutan to move from point to point through canopy at the swampy area, following the animal from the ground can be difficult. There is a good chance that surveyors could not catch up with the animal and lose sight of it during the follow. While using passive detectors such as camera-trap (Loken, Spehar, and Rayadin 2013; Ancrenaz et al. 2014) and the bioacoustic sensor for monitoring orangutans and orther primates have become increasingly popular. However, its application is still at an infant state, and researchers do not yet fully understand its practicality and effectiveness.

Surveying orangutan nest is much easier than the animal itself, and many surveyors actually preferred this approach. The question is, can I use the nest as a proxy for monitoring animal movement? Since orangutan leaves a trail of nests as it moves through the forest, it might be possible to trace the animals movement pattern. IF new and unmarked nests are found during a repeat visit at the transects, I can assume that the animal had re-located or moved since the last visit. Also, because new nests are built daily I would expect to see somewhat active movement by the animal throughout the study period.

Because I wanted to know whether orangutans move between two Totally Protected Areas (TPAs), I need to survey areas adjacent to the proposed wildlife corridor, including the TPAs. This is to verify whether 1) the animals used TPAs recently and 2) the animals not using different pathways to go across TPAs. The transect spacing is the average daily distance range of adult orangutans (Davies et al. 2017; Oram 2018) or shorter to increase nest detection. The survey interval is long enough to allow the animals to roam around and build new nest clusters at different locations. The surveys must be done at least three times for consistency (~Law of averages). Since I am interested in re-distribution of nests, all nest classes will be recorded. More importantly, I want all nests GPS coordinates and nesting trees marked accurately and labeled clearly. If orangutans do move between TPAs, I should see new nest clusters popping up inside the proposed wildlife corridor at different sampling sessions, like in example shown below.


Fit Penalised Regression Splines (PRS) using the function in the package (Wood 2017) in , and use coefficients from the models to predict count for the entire environment at different phases.

#Fit Penalised Regression Splines (PRS)
fit1 <- gam(count ~ s(x) + s(y), family = poisson, data = data[data$session == "A",])
fit2 <- gam(count ~ s(x) + s(y), family = poisson, data = data[data$session == "B",])
fit3 <- gam(count ~ s(x) + s(y), family = poisson, data = data[data$session == "C",])

#Use coefficients to predict
surveyA <- predict(fit1, type = "response", se.fit = TRUE, newdata = study_area)
surveyB <- predict(fit2, type = "response", se.fit = TRUE, newdata = study_area)
surveyC <- predict(fit3, type = "response", se.fit = TRUE, newdata = study_area)

Similar to Species Distribution Modeling (SDM), this analysis tells us which part of the environment will likely have more nests. I think improving the prediction includes using non-Euclidean movement (Sutherland, Fuller, and Royle 2015), rasters that depict anthropogenic influence on the environment (Palminteri et al. 2012; Manduell, Harrison, and Thorpe 2012), and Bayesian analysis (Wade 2000), but I will try out these ideas later when I have more time to run the simulations. The bottom line is that I assume orangutans utilize areas with more nests. So, the proposed wildlife corridor should prioritize these areas instead. P/S: Dont pay too much attention to the maps for now as the simulated data for analysis were too simplistic.

Note

Because nest is used as indicator, there are some cause of concerns. Orangutan movement between TPAS may have gone unnoticed if:
- daily distance range is more extensive than length of the proposed wildlife corridor. In that case, it is actually unnecessary to rest and build nests inside it.
- disturbance level at the proposed wildlife corridor is high, so orangutan prefer to avoid resting and building nests inside it.
- nest decay rate is too high, such new nest clusters built after a sampling occasion are completely perished before the next session.
